GENOME SEQUENCING REPORT

NDM carbapenemase analysis for hospital site XX

Report generated on 2024-08-07

SUMMARY

  • Thirty-four isolates comprising seventeen Enterobacter cloacae, seven Escherichia coli, four Citrobacter freundii, two Klebsiella variicola, one Klebsiella oxytoca, and two Klebsiella pneumoniae had a blaNDM gene (Table 1)
  • Three blaNDM variants (twelve blaNDM-1, five blaNDM-5, nineteen blaNDM-7) were observed across nine plasmid types
  • blaNDM-7 is predicted to be transmitted through both clonal transmission and plasmid transmission
    • Plasmid transmission:
      • A blaNDM-7 gene on an IncX3 plasmid was present in nineteen isolates of different species and sequence types
    • Clonal transmission:
      • Nine Enterobacter cloacae isolates were ST1690, differed by 0 - 4 SNVs (Figure 2), and had the blaNDM-7 gene on an IncX3 plasmid
      • Two Enterobacter cloacae isolates were ST536, differed by 0 SNVs, and had the blaNDM-7 gene on an IncX3 plasmid
  • blaNDM-1 is predicted to be transmitted through both clonal transmission and plasmid transmission
    • Plasmid transmission:
      • A blaNDM-1 gene on an IncHI2/HI2A plasmid was present in four isolates of different species.
      • A blaNDM-1 gene on an IncC plasmid was present in three isolates of different species.
    • Clonal transmission:
      • Three Citrobacter freundii isolates were the same novel sequence type, differed by 1 - 21 SNVs (Figure 4, and had the blaNDM-1 gene on an IncHI2/HI2A plasmid
      • Two Klebsiella variicola isolates were ST925, differed by 1 SNV, and had the blaNDM-1 gene on an IncFIB/FII plasmid
      • Three Enterobacter cloacae isolates were ST45, differed by 0 or 4 SNVs (Figure 5), and had the blaNDM-1 gene on an IncFIB/FII plasmid. One isolate (N23-00046) had that plasmid integrated into the chromosome.
  • blaNDM-5 is predicted to be transmitted through clonal transmission
    • Clonal transmission:
      • Three Escherichia coli isolates were ST167, differed by 2 SNVs, had the blaNDM-5 gene on an IncFIA/FIB plasmid (Figure 3)
  • Based on the results above, it is recommended to further investigate linkages using epidemiological data to confirm clonal and plasmid transmission

PHYLOGENETIC CLUSTERING ANALYSIS

Phylogenetic analysis was conducted using the SNVPhyl pipeline on all isolates of the same species that shared the same sequence type (ST): E. cloacae ST1690, E. cloacae ST45, E. cloacae ST536, E. coli ST167, C. freundii novel1, and K. variicola ST925.

The Enterobacter cloacae ST1690 tree was conducted using N23-01755 as a reference and 91.58 % of the core genome. 0-4 single nucleotide variants (SNVs) were observed between these isolates (Figure 2).

The Escherichia coli ST167 tree was conducted using N23-02657 as a reference and 98.37 % of the core genome. 2 SNVs were observed between these isolates (Figure 3).

The Citrobacter freundii novel1 tree was conducted using N23-02659 as the reference and 97.05 % of the core genome. 1, 20 or 21 SNVs were observed between these isolates (Figure 4).

The Enterobacter cloacae ST45 tree was conducted using N23-02070 as the reference and 94.77% of the core genome. 0 or 4 SNVs were observed between three isolates. N24-01108 was 356 - 358 SNVs from this cluster (not shown), suggesting this isolate is unrelated to the others (Figure 5).

In addition, SNV analysis was performed on the following pairs of isolates (figures not shown):

  • Klebsiella variicola ST925: using N23-02352 as the reference, SNV analysis found 1 SNV compared to N23-02353 when using 95.63 % of the core genome. This SNV was in the pgi housekeeping gene which is used to call sequence types.
  • Enterobacter cloacae ST536: using N23-01962 as the reference, SNV analysis found 1 SNV compared to N23-01961 when using 99.28 % of the core genome.

Figure 2: Maximum-Likelihood Tree (PhyML) based on SNVs from a multi-sequence alignment for Enterobacter cloacae ST1690 isolates. Asterisks (*) indicates the reference genome.

Figure 3: Maximum-Likelihood Tree (PhyML) based on SNVs from a multi-sequence alignment for Escherichia coli ST167 isolates. Asterisks (*) indicates the reference genome.

Figure 4: Maximum-Likelihood Tree (PhyML) based on SNVs from a multi-sequence alignment for Citrobacter freundii ST novel1 isolates. Asterisks (*) indicates the reference genome.

Figure 5: Maximum-Likelihood Tree (PhyML) based on SNVs from a multi-sequence alignment for Enterobacter cloacae ST45 isolates. Asterisks (*) indicates the reference genome.

PLASMID PANGENOMES

Plasmid sequence content was compared within each plasmid cluster by using BLAST to compare to a reference plasmid (pN24-00692). Core genes are present within each plasmid whereas variable accessory genes present only in select isolates will be indicated by gaps.

The structure of the blaNDM-7-encoding plasmids from Plasmid Cluster #1 and Epi Cluster #3 are shown in Figure 6. Plasmid CDSs are identical.

Figure 6: Plasmid structure of blaNDM-7-encoding IncX3 46 kb plasmids from Plasmid Cluster #1 and Epi Cluster #3.

DISCLAIMER

  • Testing was performed, in whole or in part using a research-based test.
  • Whole genome sequencing is not an ISO accredited test and results are validated and measured for quality based on in-house workflows.
  • Interpretation of the results are based on in-house workflows.
  • Some isolates are from the same individuals.

DATA DICTIONARY

Phylogenetic Analysis

  • Phylogenetic analysis was conducted using the paired-end SNVPhyl pipeline v1.2.3 (https://github.com/phac-nml/snvphyl-tools) using the following parameters:
    • Minimum base coverage: 10
    • Minimum mapping quality score: 30
    • Relative SNV abundance ratio: 0.75
    • Window size for SNV density filtering: 20
  • Labels, where applicable, represent: Environmental (E), Clinical (C), Sequence Type (ST), Date of isolation (YYYY-MM-DD).
  • Core: the percent of the genome shared by all isolates that is used for phylogenetic analysis.
    • Percent core is shown for overall trees generated for each hospital as well as individual clusters.
  • Approximate SNV distances are shown between branches and represent closest distance between clusters* in some cases
    • *clusters are defined as >2 isolates within a sequence type.
  • Matrix data and SNV distances presented on specific clusters are true value based on sub-clustering analysis**
    • **sub-clustering was conducting buy running the SNVPhyl pipeline on specific clusters of interest using an internal reference within each cluster.
  • Phylogenetic trees only shown for three or more isolates.

Methods

  • Illumina libraries were created with Nextera XT kits where paired-end 150bp indexed reads were generated on an Illumina NextSeq2000 platform using the v2.5 (300 cycles) preparation kits. Oxford Nanopore Technologies sequencing libraries were prepped using the Rapid Barcoding kit (SQK-RBK004 or SQK-RBK114.24) and R9.4.1 or R10.4.1 flowcells. Reads were basecalled using the super accurate model (SUP) with Guppy v6.5.7. De novo assemblies were completed using Unicycler v0.5.0 (https://github.com/rrwick/Unicycler) or Flye v2.9.2 (https://github.com/fenderglass/Flye).
  • Assembled sequence data was analyzed for Multi Locus Sequence Typing (MLST), antimicrobial resistance genes and plasmid typing with a 90 % identity cut-off using StarAMR v0.10.0 (https://github.com/phac-nml/staramr) and the PointFinder database (https://bitbucket.org/genomicepidemiology/pointfinder/src/master/) (if applicable). Organism identification is based on refseqMasher (https://github.com/phac-nml/refseq_masher) or FastANI (https://github.com/ParBLiSS/FastANI).
  • Plasmids were clustered using MOB-suite v3.1.5 (https://github.com/phac-nml/mob-suite) with the default secondary cluster Mash distance of 0.025.
  • Where plasmids are compared to external references: Each plasmid was extracted from the assembly and queried against the PLSDB plasmid database (https://ccb-microbe.cs.uni-saarland.de/plsdb/), using MASH to identify closed known plasmids to compare against client submitted cases.
  • Tn4401 is the transposition unit on which the blaKPC gene is mobilized. It aids the gene in moving between plasmids and thus species. We used TETyper (https://github.com/aesheppard/TETyper) to determine the Tn4401 variant as a method of typing KPC cases.

Data Visualization

  • All plasmid figures are generated on Proksee (https://proksee.ca/) or GView (https://server.gview.ca/) to compare CDS regions between selected plasmids.
    • Note: not all coding sequences are labelled in the figures.

Definitions

  • Clonal transmission: occurs when the same organism, indicated by species and MLST type (ex. E. coli ST405) and the same plasmid (if applicable), indicated by same carbapenemase and plasmid type (ex: NDM-1 IncA/C) are transmitted.

  • Plasmid transmission: occurs when only the plasmid harbouring the resistance gene of interest is transmitted. This can occur within the same species but different MLST types (ex: plasmid NDM-1 IncA/C in E. coli ST405 and E. coli ST410) or between species (ex: plasmid NDM-1 IncA/C in E. coli ST405 and K. pneumoniae ST15).
